The '''Rotary Lombardi Award''' is an award for [[college football]] in the [[United States]]. Awarded by the [[Rotary International|Rotary Club]] of [[Houston|Houston, Texas]] annually to the college football player "who best embodies the values and spirit of NFL's legendary coach [[Vince Lombardi]]"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rookieroad.com/football/trophies-and-awards/lombardi-award/|title = Football Lombardi Award}}</ref> the Rotary Lombardi Award program was created in 1970 shortly after the death of Lombardi.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Rotary Lombardi Award|journal=The Rotarian|date=December 1995|volume=167|issue=6|page=34|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MjEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA34|access-date=July 16, 2017|publisher=Rotary International|issn=0035-838X}}</ref> The committee outlined the original criteria for eligibility for the award, which remained in place until this day:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chron.com/sports/cougars/article/College-football-s-Lombardi-Award-to-be-open-to-9182486.php|title = College football's Lombardi Award to be open to all positions|date = 24 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2016/08/the_heisman-like_college_footb.html|title = The Heisman-like college football award for anti-Manziels|date = 27 August 2016}}</ref>

== History ==
Following the death of highly regarded football coach Vince Lombardi in 1970 his widow, Marie, authorised the Rotary Club of Houston to establish the Rotary Lombardi Award. The award began as recognition to only [[Lineman (gridiron football)|interior line]] positions that Vince Lombardi played while an undergraduate at [[Fordham University]], offensive and defensive guard, and later expanded to include [[linebacker]]s and [[tight end]]s, with the addition of including non-performance values: leadership, courage, desire, respect for authority, and discipline.

To be considered for the award, players must be an [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|NCAA FBS]] College Football team member and meet the following qualifications:

* Be a down [[Lineman (gridiron football)|Lineman]], end to end, either on offense or defense, setting up no further than ten yards to the left or right of the ball at the time of the [[Snap (gridiron football)|snap]].
* Be a [[Linebacker]] on defense, setting up no further than five yards deep from the [[line of scrimmage]]. 
* Must not come out of the [[offensive backfield]] and set up on the line of scrimmage as a Blocker or a Receiver or listed in the program as an Offensive Back or Receiver.
* Be eligible to participate in the current season.

The voting electorate is made up of the head coaches from all [[NCAA Division I]] schools, sports media personnel from across the country, and former winners and finalists of the Lombardi Award. The total number of voters is approximately 500.<ref>{{cite news|title=Texas' Orakpo wins Lombardi Award|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire/_/section/ncf/id/3761321|access-date=July 16, 2017|work=ESPN.com|agency=Associated Press|date=December 10, 2008}}</ref> The [[Ohio State University]] holds the record for most Lombardi awards with six. [[Orlando Pace]], the only two-time winner (1995 and 1996), was the most recent offensive lineman to be honored until 2024, when Kelvin Banks, Jr. of the Texas Longhorns took home the award. 

Net proceeds from the award activities are contributed to [[cancer]] research, awareness, and treatment, on the stipulation of Marie Lombardi.

=== Expansion of candidates, then retraction ===
In 2017, the presenting Rotary Club expanded the award's eligibility to include all positions.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Duarte|first=Joseph|date=2016-08-24|title=College football's Lombardi Award to be open to all positions|url=https://www.chron.com/sports/cougars/article/College-football-s-Lombardi-Award-to-be-open-to-9182486.php|access-date=2021-12-07|website=Chron|language=en-US}}</ref> This lasted until 2021, when they  reverted to the original criteria. The winners from 2017 through 2020 are not recognized by the current award committee, although 2020 winner [[Zaven Collins]] qualified under the original criteria.<ref>{{Cite web|title=MEDIA|url=https://www.rotarylombardiaward.org/copy-of-watchlist|access-date=2021-12-07|website=RotaryLombardiAward|language=en}}</ref>
